{
  "text": "understood. Reported effects of IF-AEF include the arrest of cell proliferation, sensitization of tumour cells to chemotherapy and regulation of immune function. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] A functioning vascular supply is essential for the continued growth of solid tumours, which would otherwise remain dormant. [CITATION_3] The therapeutic potential of interfering with the vasculature is both widely recognized and highly promising. Nanosecond pulsed electric fields have been shown to reduce tumour blood supply, [CITATION_4] but other researchers have found that electric fields can induce angiogenesis. [CITATION_5] The aim of the present study was to determine whether IF-AEF could alter tumour blood supply. Suspensions of a murine melanoma cell line (B16F10) and subcutaneously induced tumours were exposed to IF-AEF, and the effects on apoptosis and angiogenesis were investigated.",
  "correct_citation": {
